# CODEOWNERS - auto-assigns human reviewers to PRs (Tenacious Standard §1, §2).
# Fixes the "no human review" gap: a human is pulled onto sensitive changes.
# GitHub requests reviewers by matching the FILES a PR changes to the patterns
# below. Branch protection then requires their approval (main needs 2).
#
# ============================================================================
# HOW TO FILL THIS IN  (do one of the two styles, then delete the unused one)
#
#   Left side  = file pattern (which files trigger the review)
#   Right side = the reviewer(s): a @username OR a @org/team
#   Put TWO names on one line to require BOTH (e.g. Tech Lead AND Owner).
#
#   STYLE A - individual people (quickest, single repo):
#       replace  @your-tech-lead     with the Tech Lead's GitHub username
#       replace  @your-project-owner with the Project Owner's GitHub username
#
#   STYLE B - GitHub teams (best org-wide; create the teams first):
#       replace  @your-tech-lead     with  @your-org/tech-leads
#       replace  @your-project-owner with  @your-org/project-owners
#
#   The people/teams MUST have access to the repo, or GitHub ignores them.
#   (The Tacit's bootstrapper can fill these in per project automatically.)
# ============================================================================

# Default reviewer for everything - usually the Tech Lead.
*                   @your-tech-lead

# Sensitive surfaces (Standard §1 risk areas) - Tech Lead reviews.
# Rename these folders to match your project's actual structure.
**/auth/**          @your-tech-lead
**/security/**      @your-tech-lead
**/migrations/**    @your-tech-lead
**/alembic/**       @your-tech-lead
/.github/**         @your-tech-lead

# Highest-risk areas - require BOTH Tech Lead AND Project Owner.
# (Two names on the line = both are requested; main requires 2 approvals.)
**/billing/**       @your-tech-lead @your-project-owner
**/payments/**      @your-tech-lead @your-project-owner
